3538_163624_000006_000000 THE STORY OF SIGURD
3538_163624_000007_000001 They have carved on the rocks pictures of some of the things that happen in the tale, and those carvings may still be seen.
3538_163624_000007_000002 Because it is so old and so beautiful the story is told here again, but it has a sad ending-indeed it is all sad, and all about fighting and killing, as might be expected from the Danes.)
3538_163624_000008_000000 ONCE upon a time there was a King in the North who had won many wars, but now he was old.
3538_163624_000008_000002 The old King went out and fought bravely, but at last his sword broke, and he was wounded and his men fled.
3538_163624_000008_000003 But in the night, when the battle was over, his young wife came out and searched for him among the slain, and at last she found him, and asked whether he might be healed.
3538_163624_000008_000004 But he said 'No,' his luck was gone, his sword was broken, and he must die.
3538_163624_000009_000000 Then he died.
3538_163624_000009_000001 And his wife called her maid to her and said, 'Let us change clothes, and you shall be called by my name, and I by yours, lest the enemy finds us.'
3538_163624_000010_000000 So this was done, and they hid in a wood, but there some strangers met them and carried them off in a ship to Denmark.
3538_163624_000010_000001 And when they were brought before the King, he thought the maid looked like a Queen, and the Queen like a maid.
3538_163624_000010_000002 So he asked the Queen, 'How do you know in the dark of night whether the hours are wearing to the morning?'
3538_163624_000011_000000 And she said:
3538_163624_000013_000000 'A strange Queen to light the fires,' thought the King.
3538_163624_000015_000000 'My father gave me a gold ring,' said she, 'and always, ere the dawning, it grows cold on my finger.'
3538_163624_000016_000000 'A rich house where the maids wore gold,' said the King. 'Truly you are no maid, but a King's daughter.'
3538_163624_000017_000000 So he treated her royally, and as time went on she had a son called Sigurd, a beautiful boy and very strong.
3538_163624_000017_000001 He had a tutor to be with him, and once the tutor bade him go to the King and ask for a horse.
3538_163624_000019_000000 Then the old man said, 'Drive all the horses into the river, and choose the one that swims across.'
3538_163624_000020_000000 So Sigurd drove them, and only one swam across.
3538_163624_000020_000001 Sigurd chose him: his name was Grani, and he came of Sleipnir's breed, and was the best horse in the world.
3538_163624_000020_000002 For Sleipnir was the horse of Odin, the God of the North, and was as swift as the wind.
3538_163624_000021_000000 But a day or two later his tutor said to Sigurd, 'There is a great treasure of gold hidden not far from here, and it would become you to win it.'
3538_163624_000025_000000 Then his tutor, whose name was Regin, told him that all this great hoard of red gold had once belonged to his own father.
3538_163624_000026_000000 Now there was at that time a dwarf called Andvari, who lived in a pool beneath a waterfall, and there he had hidden a great hoard of gold.
3538_163624_000026_000001 And one day Otter had been fishing there, and had killed a salmon and eaten it, and was sleeping, like an otter, on a stone.
3538_163624_000026_000004 Then the person who had killed Otter went down and caught the Dwarf who owned all the treasure and took it from him.
3538_163624_000027_000000 Only one ring was left, which the Dwarf wore, and even that was taken from him.
3538_163624_000029_000000 Then the otter skin was filled with gold and covered with gold, all but one hair, and that was covered with the poor Dwarf's last ring.
3538_163624_000030_000000 But it brought good luck to nobody.
3538_163624_000030_000001 First Fafnir, the Dragon, killed his own father, and then he went and wallowed on the gold, and would let his brother have none, and no man dared go near it.
3538_163624_000031_000000 When Sigurd heard the story he said to Regin:
3538_163624_000032_000000 'Make me a good sword that I may kill this Dragon.'
3538_163624_000033_000000 So Regin made a sword, and Sigurd tried it with a blow on a lump of iron, and the sword broke.
3538_163624_000034_000000 Another sword he made, and Sigurd broke that too.
3538_163624_000035_000001 And he hammered and wrought them into a new sword, so sharp that fire seemed to burn along its edges.
3538_163624_000036_000000 Sigurd tried this blade on the lump of iron, and it did not break, but split the iron in two.
3538_163624_000036_000001 Then he threw a lock of wool into the river, and when it floated down against the sword it was cut into two pieces.
3538_163624_000036_000002 So Sigurd said that sword would do.
3538_163624_000037_000000 When he had been at home a few days, he rode out with Regin one morning to the heath where the Dragon used to lie.
3538_163624_000037_000001 Then he saw the track which the Dragon made when he went to a cliff to drink, and the track was as if a great river had rolled along and left a deep valley.
3538_163624_000038_000000 Then Sigurd went down into that deep place, and dug many pits in it, and in one of the pits he lay hidden with his sword drawn.
3538_163624_000038_000001 There he waited, and presently the earth began to shake with the weight of the Dragon as he crawled to the water.
3538_163624_000039_000000 But Sigurd waited till half of him had crawled over the pit, and then he thrust the sword Gram right into his very heart.
3538_163624_000040_000000 Then the Dragon lashed with his tail till stones broke and trees crashed about him.
3538_163624_000041_000000 Then he spoke, as he died, and said:
3538_163624_000043_000000 Sigurd said:
3538_163624_000044_000000 'I would touch none of it if by losing it I should never die.
3538_163624_000044_000001 But all men die, and no brave man lets death frighten him from his desire.
3538_163624_000045_000000 And after that Sigurd was called Fafnir's Bane, and Dragonslayer.
