3538_163624_000063_000004 Then Sigurd rode away, and he came to the house of a King who had a fair daughter.
3538_163624_000064_000003 Then Gunnar tried Sigurd's horse Grani, but he would not move with Gunnar on his back.
3538_163624_000065_000000 Now Brynhild had no help but to promise she would be his wife, the wife of Gunnar as she supposed, for Sigurd wore Gunnar's shape, and she had sworn to wed whoever should ride the flames.
3538_163624_000065_000004 'Yet I thought,' she said, 'that no man could have done this deed but Sigurd, Fafnir's bane, who was my true love.
3538_163624_000065_000005 But he has forgotten me, and my promise I must keep.'
3538_163624_000066_000000 So Gunnar and Brynhild were married, though it was not Gunnar but Sigurd in Gunnar's shape, that had ridden the fire.
3538_163624_000067_000000 And when the wedding was over and all the feast, then the magic of the witch's wine went out of Sigurd's brain, and he remembered all.
3538_163624_000068_000000 But he was brave, and he spoke not a word of it to the others to make them unhappy.
3538_163624_000069_000002 For her husband, she said, had ridden through the flame when no other man dared face it.
3538_163624_000071_000000 Then Brynhild saw the ring which Sigard had given to Gudrun, and she knew it and knew all, and she turned as pale as a dead woman, and went home.
3538_163624_000071_000001 All that evening she never spoke.
3538_163624_000071_000003 And she said he would never see her glad in his hall, never drinking wine, never playing chess, never embroidering with the golden thread, never speaking words of kindness.
3538_163624_000071_000004 Then she rent all her needlework asunder and wept aloud, so that everyone in the house heard her.
3538_163624_000075_000000 'It is too late.'
3538_163624_000076_000000 Then Sigurd was so grieved and his heart so swelled in his breast that it burst the steel rings of his shirt of mail.
3538_163624_000077_000000 Sigurd went out and Brynhild determined to slay him.
