3764_168671_000005_000000 The Vaugirard cemetery formed an exception among the cemeteries of Paris.
3764_168671_000005_000002 The grave diggers being thus bound to service in the evening in summer and at night in winter, in this cemetery, they were subjected to a special discipline.
3764_168671_000005_000003 The gates of the Paris cemeteries closed, at that epoch, at sundown, and this being a municipal regulation, the Vaugirard cemetery was bound by it like the rest.
3764_168671_000005_000006 If any grave digger were delayed after that moment in the cemetery, there was but one way for him to get out-his grave digger's card furnished by the department of public funerals.
3764_168671_000005_000007 A sort of letter box was constructed in the porter's window. The grave digger dropped his card into this box, the porter heard it fall, pulled the rope, and the small door opened.
3764_168671_000005_000008 If the man had not his card, he mentioned his name, the porter, who was sometimes in bed and asleep, rose, came out and identified the man, and opened the gate with his key; the grave digger stepped out, but had to pay a fine of fifteen francs.
3764_168671_000006_000000 This cemetery, with its peculiarities outside the regulations, embarrassed the symmetry of the administration.
3764_168671_000006_000001 It was suppressed a little later than eighteen thirty.
