4350_10919_000012_000000 The family doctor respectfully ceased in the middle of his observations.
4350_10919_000013_000000 "The commencement of the tuberculous process we are not, as you are aware, able to define; till there are cavities, there is nothing definite.
4350_10919_000013_000001 But we may suspect it.
4350_10919_000013_000002 And there are indications; malnutrition, nervous excitability, and so on.
4350_10919_000013_000003 The question stands thus: in presence of indications of tuberculous process, what is to be done to maintain nutrition?"
4350_10919_000015_000000 "Yes, that's an understood thing," responded the celebrated physician, again glancing at his watch.
4350_10919_000015_000001 "Beg pardon, is the Yausky bridge done yet, or shall I have to drive around?" he asked.
4350_10919_000015_000002 "Ah! it is.
4350_10919_000015_000003 Oh, well, then I can do it in twenty minutes.
4350_10919_000015_000004 So we were saying the problem may be put thus: to maintain nutrition and to give tone to the nerves.
4350_10919_000016_000000 "And how about a tour abroad?" asked the family doctor.
4350_10919_000017_000000 "I've no liking for foreign tours.
4350_10919_000018_000000 The family doctor listened attentively and respectfully.
4350_10919_000019_000000 "But in favor of foreign travel I would urge the change of habits, the removal from conditions calling up reminiscences.
4350_10919_000020_000001 Well, in that case, to be sure, let them go.
4350_10919_000020_000002 Only, those German quacks are mischievous....
4350_10919_000020_000003 They ought to be persuaded....
4350_10919_000022_000000 "Oh! time's up already," And he went to the door.
4350_10919_000022_000001 The celebrated doctor announced to the princess (a feeling of what was due from him dictated his doing so) that he ought to see the patient once more.
4350_10919_000024_000000 "Oh, no, only a few details, princess."
4350_10919_000025_000000 "Come this way."
4350_10919_000026_000000 And the mother, accompanied by the doctor, went into the drawing room to Kitty.
4350_10919_000026_000001 Wasted and flushed, with a peculiar glitter in her eyes, left there by the agony of shame she had been put through, Kitty stood in the middle of the room.
4350_10919_000026_000002 When the doctor came in she flushed crimson, and her eyes filled with tears.
4350_10919_000026_000003 All her illness and treatment struck her as a thing so stupid, ludicrous even!
4350_10919_000026_000004 Doctoring her seemed to her as absurd as putting together the pieces of a broken vase.
4350_10919_000026_000005 Her heart was broken. Why would they try to cure her with pills and powders?
4350_10919_000026_000006 But she could not grieve her mother, especially as her mother considered herself to blame.
4350_10919_000028_000000 He sat down with a smile, facing her, felt her pulse, and again began asking her tiresome questions.
4350_10919_000028_000001 She answered him, and all at once got up, furious.
4350_10919_000029_000000 "Excuse me, doctor, but there is really no object in this.
4350_10919_000029_000001 This is the third time you've asked me the same thing."
4350_10919_000030_000000 The celebrated doctor did not take offense.
4350_10919_000031_000001 "However, I had finished..."
4350_10919_000032_000000 And the doctor began scientifically explaining to the princess, as an exceptionally intelligent woman, the condition of the young princess, and concluded by insisting on the drinking of the waters, which were certainly harmless.
4350_10919_000032_000002 the doctor plunged into deep meditation, as though resolving a weighty problem. Finally his decision was pronounced: they were to go abroad, but to put no faith in foreign quacks, and to apply to him in any need.
4350_10919_000033_000000 It seemed as though some piece of good fortune had come to pass after the doctor had gone.
4350_10919_000033_000001 The mother was much more cheerful when she went back to her daughter, and Kitty pretended to be more cheerful.
4350_9170_000001_000000 This is absolutely incorrect.
4350_9170_000002_000000 The social conception of life, we have seen, consists in the transfer of the aim of life from the individual to groups and their maintenance-to the tribe, family, race, or state.
4350_9170_000003_000000 In the social conception of life it is supposed that since the aim of life is found in groups of individuals, individuals will voluntarily sacrifice their own interests for the interests of the group.
4350_9170_000003_000001 And so it has been, and still is, in fact, in certain groups, the distinction being that they are the most primitive forms of association in the family or tribe or race, or even in the patriarchal state.
4350_9170_000004_000001 The champions of the social conception of life usually try to connect the idea of authority, that is, of violence, with the idea of moral influence, but this connection is quite impossible.
4350_9170_000005_000000 The effect of moral influence on a man is to change his desires and to bend them in the direction of the duty required of him. The man who is controlled by moral influence acts in accordance with his own desires.
4350_9170_000005_000001 Authority, in the sense in which the word is ordinarily understood, is a means of forcing a man to act in opposition to his desires.
4350_9170_000005_000003 Nothing can oblige a man to do what he does not choose except physical force, or the threat of it, that is-deprivation of freedom, blows, imprisonment, or threats-easily carried out-of such punishments.
4350_9170_000007_000000 The basis of authority is bodily violence.
4350_9170_000007_000001 The possibility of applying bodily violence to people is provided above all by an organization of armed men, trained to act in unison in submission to one will.
4350_9170_000007_000002 These bands of armed men, submissive to a single will, are what constitute the army.
4350_9170_000007_000003 The army has always been and still is the basis of power.
4350_9170_000007_000004 Power is always in the hands of those who control the army, and all men in power-from the Roman Caesars to the Russian and German Emperors-take more interest in their army than in anything, and court popularity in the army, knowing that if that is on their side their power is secure.
4350_9170_000011_000000 All the methods of appointing authorities that have been tried, divine right, and election, and heredity, and balloting, and assemblies and parliaments and senate-have all proved ineffectual.
4350_9170_000011_000003 Indeed, it could not be otherwise.
4350_9170_000013_000001 Only under those conditions could the social organization be justified.
4350_9170_000015_000001 As the disposition of individuals to violence diminished, and as the habits of the people became more civilized, and as power grew more social organization demoralized through lack of restraint, this advantage disappeared.
4350_9170_000017_000000 This, put simply, is how it has come to pass.
4350_9170_000018_000002 The larger and stronger groups conquered and absorbed the weaker, and the larger and stronger they became, the more internal feuds disappeared and the more the continuity of the group seemed assured.
4350_9170_000019_000000 The members of a family or tribe, united into one community, are less hostile among themselves, and families and tribes do not die like one man, but have a continuity of existence.
4350_9170_000020_000001 It was produced, on one hand, by the natural growth of population, and, on the other, by struggle and conquest.
4350_9170_000021_000000 After conquest the power of the emperor puts an end to internal dissensions, and so the state conception of life justifies itself. But this justification is never more than temporary.
4350_9170_000021_000001 Internal dissensions disappear only in proportion to the degree of oppression exerted by the authority over the dissentient individuals.
4350_9170_000022_000000 Government authority, even if it does suppress private violence, always introduces into the life of men fresh forms of violence, which tend to become greater and greater in proportion to the duration and strength of the government.
4350_9170_000025_000000 And therefore the oppression of the oppressed always goes on growing up to the furthest limit, beyond which it cannot go without killing the goose with the golden eggs.
4350_9170_000025_000001 And if the goose lays no more eggs, like the American Indians, negroes, and Fijians, then it is killed in spite of the sincere protests of philanthropists.
4350_9170_000026_000000 The most convincing example of this is to be found in the condition of the working classes of our epoch, who are in reality no better than the slaves of ancient times subdued by conquest.
4350_9170_000028_000000 So it has always been.
4350_9170_000030_000000 Such has been and still is the condition of all the oppressed, but hitherto they have not recognized the fact.
4350_9170_000031_000000 People have believed, as though it were something fully proved, and so needing no proof, that since all nations have hitherto developed in the form of states, that form of organization is an indispensable condition of the development of humanity.
4350_9170_000033_000000 So it was under the Roman emperors and so it is now.
4350_9170_000033_000001 In spite of the fact that the sense of the uselessness and even injurious effects of state violence is more and more penetrating into men's consciousness, things might have gone on in the same way forever if governments were not under the necessity of constantly increasing their armies in order to maintain their power.
4350_9170_000035_000000 That has always been necessary, and has become more and more necessary with the increased diffusion of education among the masses, with the improved communication between people of the same and of different nationalities.
4350_9170_000035_000001 It has become particularly indispensable now in the face of communism, socialism, anarchism, and the labor movement generally.
4350_9170_000035_000002 Governments feel that it is so, and strengthen the force of their disciplined armies.
4350_9170_000035_000003 [See Footnote]
4350_9170_000037_000000 In the German Reichstag not long ago, in reply to a question why funds were needed for raising the salaries of the under officers, the German Chancellor openly declared that trustworthy under officers were necessary to contend against socialism.
4350_9170_000037_000001 Caprivi only said aloud what every statesman knows and assiduously conceals from the people.
4350_9170_000037_000003 The meaning of Caprivi's speech, put into plain language, is that funds are needed, not to resist foreign foes, but to BUY UNDER OFFICERS to be ready to act against the enslaved toiling masses.
4350_9170_000038_000000 Caprivi incautiously gave utterance to what everyone knows perfectly well, or at least feels vaguely if he does not recognize it, that is, that the existing order of life is as it is, not, as would be natural and right, because the people wish it to be so, but because it is so maintained by state violence, by the army with its BOUGHT UNDER OFFICERS and generals.
4350_9170_000039_000001 And this abnormal order of things is maintained by the army.
4350_9170_000040_000000 Everyone, if he does not recognize this now, will know that it is so at the first attempt at insubordination or at a revolution of the existing order.
4350_9170_000042_000000 To keep their subjects in oppression and to be able to enjoy the fruits of their labor the government must have armed forces.
4350_9170_000043_000000 But there is not only one government.
4350_9170_000043_000002 And so every government needs an army also to protect its booty from its neighbor brigands.
4350_9170_000043_000003 Every government is thus involuntarily reduced to the necessity of emulating one another in the increase of their armies.
4350_9170_000044_000000 Every increase in the army of one state, with the aim of self defense against its subjects, becomes a source of danger for neighboring states and calls for a similar increase in their armies.
4350_9170_000046_000000 Both causes, mutually dependent, contribute to the same result at once; troops are required against internal forces and also to keep up a position with other states.
4350_9170_000046_000001 One is the result of the other. The despotism of a government always increases with the strength of the army and its external successes, and the aggressiveness of a government increases with its internal despotism.
4350_9170_000047_000003 And by this means all citizens are under arms to support the iniquities practiced upon them; all citizens have become their own oppressors.
4350_9170_000048_000000 Universal military service was an inevitable logical necessity, to which we were bound to come.
4350_9170_000048_000002 This inconsistency has become obvious in universal military service.
4350_9170_000049_000001 But instead of doing that they expose the individuals to the same necessity of strife, substituting strife with individuals of other states for strife with neighbors.
4350_9170_000053_000000 The taxes raised from the people for war preparations absorb the greater part of the produce of labor which the army ought to defend.
4350_9170_000054_000000 The withdrawing of all men from the ordinary course of life destroys the possibility of labor itself.
4350_9170_000054_000001 The danger of war, ever ready to break out, renders all reforms of life social life vain and fruitless.
4350_9170_000056_000000 But the fatal significance of universal military service, as the manifestation of the contradiction inherent in the social conception of life, is not only apparent in that.
4350_9170_000057_000000 Governments assert that armies are needed above all for external defense, but that is not true.
4350_9170_000058_000001 All civil outbreaks for dynastic or other party reasons, all the executions that follow on such disturbances, all repression of insurrections, and military intervention to break up meetings and to suppress strikes, all forced extortion of taxes, all the iniquitous distributions of land, all the restrictions on labor-are either carried out directly by the military or by the police with the army at their back.
4350_9170_000058_000002 Anyone who serves his time in the army shares the responsibility of all these things, about which he is, in some cases, dubious, while very often they are directly opposed to his conscience.
4350_9170_000058_000004 How can I help asking myself when I take part in such punishments, whether they are just, and whether I ought to assist in carrying them out?
4350_9170_000060_000000 The time has come when the ever growing abuse of power by governments and their struggles with one another has led to their demanding such material and even moral sacrifices from their subjects that everyone is forced to reflect and ask himself, "Can I make these sacrifices?
4350_9170_000060_000001 And for the sake of what am I making them?
4350_9170_000060_000002 I am expected for the sake of the state to make these sacrifices, to renounce everything that can be precious to man-peace, family, security, and human dignity." What is this state, for whose sake such terrible sacrifices have to be made?
4350_9170_000060_000003 And why is it so indispensably necessary?
4350_9170_000061_000000 "Except for the state," they say, "we should be exposed to the attacks of evil disposed persons in our own country."
4350_9170_000062_000000 But who are these evil disposed persons in our midst from whose attacks we are preserved by the state and its army?
4350_9170_000062_000005 So that the justification of state violence on the ground of the protection it gives us from evil disposed persons, even if it had some foundation three or four centuries ago, has none whatever now.
4350_9170_000063_000000 "Except for the state," they tell us, "we should not have any religion, education, culture, means of communication, and so on. Without the state men would not have been able to form the social institutions needed for doing any thing."
4350_9170_000063_000001 This argument too was well founded only some centuries ago.
4350_9170_000064_000002 Indeed government is more often an obstacle than an assistance in attaining these aims.
4350_9170_000065_000002 In our day governments not only fail to encourage, but directly hinder every movement by which people try to work out new forms of life for themselves.
4350_9170_000066_000000 "Without governments nations would be enslaved by their neighbors."
4350_9170_000066_000001 It is scarcely necessary to refute this last argument.
4350_9170_000066_000003 The government, they tell us, with its army, is necessary to defend us from neighboring states who might enslave us.
4350_9170_000066_000004 But we know this is what all governments say of one another, and yet we know that all the European nations profess the same principles of liberty and fraternity, and therefore stand in no need of protection against one another.
4350_9170_000066_000005 And if defense against barbarous nations is meant, one thousandth part of the troops now under arms would be amply sufficient for that purpose.
4350_9170_000066_000007 The power of the state, far from being a security against the attacks of our neighbors, exposes us, on the contrary, to much greater danger of such attacks.
4350_9170_000067_000001 Even looking at it practically, weighing, that is to say, all the burdens laid on him by the state, no man can fail to see that for him personally to comply with state demands and serve in the army, would, in the majority of cases, be more disadvantageous than to refuse to do so.
4350_9170_000068_000000 If the majority of men choose to submit rather than to refuse, it is not the result of sober balancing of advantages and disadvantages, but because they are induced by a kind of hypnotizing process practiced upon them.
4350_9170_000068_000001 In submitting they simply yield to the suggestions given them as orders, without thought or effort of will.
4350_9170_000068_000002 To resist would need independent thought and effort of which every man is not capable.
4350_9170_000068_000003 Even apart from the moral significance of compliance or non compliance, considering material advantage only, non compliance will be more advantageous in general.
4350_9170_000070_000004 So much for the comparative disadvantages.
