5683_32879_000050_000001 It was a hope.
5683_32879_000050_000002 She seized it; she clung to it.
5764_299665_000000_000001 Afterward it was supposed that he was satisfied with the blood of oxen, lambs and doves, and that in exchange for or on account of these sacrifices, this God gave rain, sunshine and harvest.
5764_299665_000000_000002 It was also believed that if the sacrifices were not made, this God sent pestilence, famine, flood and earthquake.
5764_299665_000001_000000 The last phase of this belief in sacrifice was, according to the Christian doctrine, that God accepted the blood of his son, and that after his son had been murdered, he, God, was satisfied, and wanted no more blood.
5764_299665_000002_000000 During all these years and by all these peoples it was believed that this God heard and answered prayer, that he forgave sins and saved the souls of true believers.
5764_299665_000002_000001 This, in a general way, is the definition of religion.
5764_299665_000003_000000 Now, the questions are, Whether religion was founded on any known fact?
5764_299665_000003_000001 Whether such a being as God exists?
5764_299665_000003_000002 Whether he was the creator of yourself and myself?
5764_299665_000003_000003 Whether any prayer was ever answered?
5764_299665_000003_000004 Whether any sacrifice of babe or ox secured the favor of this unseen God?
5764_299665_000005_000000 Why did he create the intellectually inferior?
5764_299665_000006_000000 Why did he create the deformed and helpless?
5764_299665_000007_000000 Why did he create the criminal, the idiotic, the insane?
5764_299665_000008_000000 Can infinite wisdom and power make any excuse for the creation of failures?
5764_299665_000009_000000 Are the failures under obligation to their creator?
5764_299665_000011_000000 Is he responsible for all the chiefs, kings, emperors, and queens?
5764_299665_000012_000000 Is he responsible for all the wars that have been waged, for all the innocent blood that has been shed?
5764_299665_000013_000000 Is he responsible for the centuries of slavery, for the backs that have been scarred with the lash, for the babes that have been sold from the breasts of mothers, for the families that have been separated and destroyed?
5764_299665_000016_000000 Did he allow his enemies to torture and burn his friends?
5764_299665_000019_000000 Can we conceive of a devil base enough to prefer his enemies to his friends?
5764_299665_000020_000000 If a good and infinitely powerful God governs this world, how can we account for cyclones, earthquakes, pestilence and famine?
5764_299665_000021_000000 How can we account for cancers, for microbes, for diphtheria and the thousand diseases that prey on infancy?
5764_299665_000025_000000 Did infinite goodness fashion the wings of the eagles so that their fleeing prey could be overtaken?
5764_299665_000026_000000 Did infinite goodness create the beasts of prey with the intention that they should devour the weak and helpless?
5764_299665_000027_000000 Did infinite goodness create the countless worthless living things that breed within and feed upon the flesh of higher forms?
5764_299665_000028_000000 Did infinite wisdom intentionally produce the microscopic beasts that feed upon the optic nerve?
5764_299665_000029_000000 Think of blinding a man to satisfy the appetite of a microbe!
5764_299665_000030_000001 Think of the victims!
5764_299665_000030_000002 Think of the Niagara of blood pouring over the precipice of cruelty!
5764_299665_000031_000000 In view of these facts, what, after all, is religion?
5764_299665_000032_000000 It is fear.
5764_299665_000035_000000 Fear bends the knees and utters the prayer.
5764_299665_000036_000000 Fear pretends to love.
5764_299665_000037_000000 Religion teaches the slave virtues-obedience, humility, self denial, forgiveness, non resistance.
5764_299665_000038_000000 Lips, religious and fearful, tremblingly repeat this passage: "Though he slay me, yet will I trust him." This is the abyss of degradation.
5764_299665_000039_000000 Religion does not teach self reliance, independence, manliness, courage, self defence.
5764_299665_000039_000001 Religion makes God a master and man his serf.
5764_299665_000039_000002 The master cannot be great enough to make slavery sweet.
5764_299665_000041_000003 He caused the sun to rise, to steal all moisture from the land, but gave no rain.
5764_299665_000041_000004 He saw the seeds that man had planted wither and perish, but he sent no rain.
5764_299665_000041_000005 He saw the people look with sad eyes upon the barren earth, and he sent no rain.
5764_299665_000041_000007 Can we say that in the heart of this God there blossomed the flower of pity?
5764_299665_000041_000008 Can we say that he cared for the children of men?
5764_299665_000042_000001 Do we prove his goodness by showing that he has opened the earth and swallowed thousands of his helpless children, or that with the volcanoes he has overwhelmed them with rivers of fire? Can we infer the goodness of God from the facts we know?
5764_299665_000043_000000 If these calamities did not happen, would we suspect that God cared nothing for human beings?
5764_299665_000043_000001 If there were no famine, no pestilence, no cyclone, no earthquake, would we think that God is not good?
5764_299665_000044_000000 According to the theologians, God did not make all men alike.
5764_299665_000044_000002 Was there goodness, was there wisdom in this?
5764_299665_000045_000001 If we say yes, then I ask another question: Should the inferior races thank God that they are not superior, or should they thank God that they are not beasts?
5764_299665_000046_000000 When God made these different races he knew that the superior would enslave the inferior, knew that the inferior would be conquered, and finally destroyed.
5764_299665_000048_000000 Why, then, should we say that God is good?
5764_299665_000050_000001 THE POWER THAT WORKS FOR RIGHTEOUSNESS.
5764_299665_000051_000000 MOST people cling to the supernatural.
5764_299665_000051_000001 If they give up one God, they imagine another.
5764_299665_000051_000002 Having outgrown Jehovah, they talk about the power that works for righteousness.
5764_299665_000052_000000 What is this power?
5764_299665_000053_000000 Man advances, and necessarily advances through experience.
5764_299665_000053_000001 A man wishing to go to a certain place comes to where the road divides.
5764_299665_000053_000002 He takes the left hand, believing it to be the right road, and travels until he finds that it is the wrong one.
5764_299665_000053_000003 He retraces his steps and takes the right hand road and reaches the place desired.
5764_299665_000053_000004 The next time he goes to the same place, he does not take the left hand road.
5764_299665_000053_000005 He has tried that road, and knows that it is the wrong road.
5764_299665_000054_000001 The hand is burned, and after that the child keeps its hand out of the fire.
5764_299665_000055_000002 It has no will, no purpose.
5764_299665_000055_000003 It is a result.
5764_299665_000056_000000 So thousands have endeavored to establish the existence of God by the fact that we have what is called the moral sense; that is to say, a conscience.
5764_299665_000057_000000 It is insisted by these theologians, and by many of the so-called philosophers, that this moral sense, this sense of duty, of obligation, was imported, and that conscience is an exotic.
5764_299665_000057_000001 Taking the ground that it was not produced here, was not produced by man, they then imagine a God from whom it came.
5764_299665_000058_000000 Man is a social being.
5764_299665_000058_000001 We live together in families, tribes and nations.
5764_299665_000059_000000 The members of a family, of a tribe, of a nation, who increase the happiness of the family, of the tribe or of the nation, are considered good members.
5764_299665_000059_000001 They are praised, admired and respected.
5764_299665_000059_000002 They are regarded as good; that is to say, as moral.
5764_299665_000060_000000 The members who add to the misery of the family, the tribe or the nation, are considered bad members.
5764_299665_000061_000000 They are blamed, despised, punished.
5764_299665_000061_000001 They are regarded as immoral.
5764_299665_000062_000000 The family, the tribe, the nation, creates a standard of conduct, of morality.
5764_299665_000062_000001 There is nothing supernatural in this.
5764_299665_000063_000000 The greatest of human beings has said, "Conscience is born of love."
5764_299665_000064_000000 The sense of obligation, of duty, was naturally produced.
5764_299665_000065_000000 Among savages, the immediate consequences of actions are taken into consideration.
5764_299665_000065_000001 As people advance, the remote consequences are perceived. The standard of conduct becomes higher.
5764_299665_000065_000002 The imagination is cultivated. A man puts himself in the place of another.
5764_299665_000065_000003 The sense of duty becomes stronger, more imperative.
5764_299665_000065_000004 Man judges himself.
5764_299665_000067_000000 Man has deceived himself.
5764_299665_000069_000000 Suppose that an infinite God exists, what can we do for him?
5764_299665_000069_000001 Being infinite, he is conditionless; being conditionless, he cannot be benefited or injured.
5764_299665_000069_000002 He cannot want.
5764_299665_000070_000000 Think of the egotism of a man who believes that an infinite being wants his praise!
5764_299665_000072_000000 WHAT has our religion done?
5764_299665_000072_000001 Of course, it is admitted by Christians that all other religions are false, and consequently we need examine only our own.
5764_299665_000073_000000 Has Christianity done good?
5764_299665_000073_000001 Has it made men nobler, more merciful, nearer honest?
5764_299665_000073_000002 When the church had control, were men made better and happier?
5764_299665_000074_000000 What has been the effect of Christianity in Italy, in Spain, in Portugal, in Ireland?
5764_299665_000075_000001 What was the effect of Christianity in Switzerland, in Holland, in Scotland, in England, in America?
5764_299665_000075_000002 Let us be honest.
5764_299665_000075_000003 Could these countries have been worse without religion?
5764_299665_000075_000004 Could they have been worse had they had any other religion than Christianity?
5764_299665_000076_000000 Would Torquemada have been worse had he been a follower of Zoroaster? Would Calvin have been more bloodthirsty if he had believed in the religion of the South Sea Islanders?
5764_299665_000076_000002 Would john Knox have been any worse had he deserted Christ and become a follower of Confucius?
5764_299665_000077_000000 Take our own dear, merciful Puritan Fathers?
5764_299665_000077_000001 What did Christianity do for them?
5764_299665_000077_000002 They hated pleasure.
5764_299665_000077_000003 On the door of life they hung the crape of death.
5764_299665_000077_000004 They muffled all the bells of gladness.
5764_299665_000077_000005 They made cradles by putting rockers on coffins.
5764_299665_000077_000006 In the Puritan year there were twelve Decembers.
5764_299665_000077_000007 They tried to do away with infancy and youth, with prattle of babes and the song of the morning.
5764_299665_000078_000000 The religion of the Puritan was an unadulterated curse.
5764_299665_000078_000002 Would the Puritan have been worse if he had adopted the religion of the North American Indians?
5764_299665_000081_000000 In this incident we see the real spirit of Protestant lovers of the Bible.
5764_299665_000081_000001 In other words, it was just as fiendish, just as infamous as the Catholic spirit.
5764_299665_000082_000000 Has the Bible made the people of Georgia kind and merciful?
5764_299665_000082_000001 Would the lynchers be more ferocious if they worshiped gods of wood and stone?
5764_299665_000084_000000 RELIGION has been tried, and in all countries, in all times, has failed.
5764_299665_000085_000000 Religion has never made man merciful.
5764_299665_000086_000000 Remember the Inquisition.
5764_299665_000090_000000 Religion has never made man free.
5764_299665_000091_000000 It has never made man moral, temperate, industrious and honest.
5764_299665_000092_000000 Are Christians more temperate, nearer virtuous, nearer honest than savages?
5764_299665_000093_000000 Among savages do we not find that their vices and cruelties are the fruits of their superstitions?
5764_299665_000094_000000 To those who believe in the Uniformity of Nature, religion is impossible.
5764_299665_000095_000000 Can we affect the nature and qualities of substance by prayer?
5764_299665_000095_000001 Can we hasten or delay the tides by worship?
5764_299665_000095_000002 Can we change winds by sacrifice? Will kneelings give us wealth?
5764_299665_000095_000003 Can we cure disease by supplication?
5764_299665_000095_000004 Can we add to our knowledge by ceremony?
5764_299665_000095_000005 Can we receive virtue or honor as alms?
5764_299665_000096_000001 Is not what we call mind just as natural as what we call body?
5764_299665_000097_000000 Religion rests on the idea that Nature has a master and that this master will listen to prayer; that this master punishes and rewards; that he loves praise and flattery and hates the brave and free.
5764_299665_000098_000000 Has man obtained any help from heaven?
5764_299665_000100_000000 IF we have a theory, we must have facts for the foundation.
5764_299665_000100_000001 We must have corner stones.
5764_299665_000100_000002 We must not build on guesses, fancies, analogies or inferences.
5764_299665_000100_000003 The structure must have a basement.
5764_299665_000100_000004 If we build, we must begin at the bottom.
5764_299665_000101_000000 I have a theory and I have four corner stones.
5764_299665_000102_000000 The first stone is that matter-substance-cannot be destroyed, cannot be annihilated.
5764_299665_000103_000000 The second stone is that force cannot be destroyed, cannot be annihilated.
5764_299665_000104_000000 The third stone is that matter and force cannot exist apart-no matter without force-no force without matter.
5764_299665_000105_000000 The fourth stone is that that which cannot be destroyed could not have been created; that the indestructible is the uncreatable.
5764_299665_000107_000000 It follows that nothing has been or can be created; that there never has been or can be a creator.
5764_299665_000108_000000 It follows that there could not have been any intelligence, any design back of matter and force.
5764_299665_000109_000000 There is no intelligence without force.
5764_299665_000109_000002 Consequently there could not by any possibility have been any intelligence, any force, back of matter.
5764_299665_000110_000000 It therefore follows that the supernatural does not and cannot exist.
5764_299665_000110_000003 In other words, it proves that man has never received any help from heaven; that all sacrifices have been in vain, and that all prayers have died unanswered in the heedless air.
5764_299665_000110_000004 I do not pretend to know.
5764_299665_000110_000005 I say what I think.
5764_299665_000112_000000 In the universe there is no chance, no caprice.
5764_299665_000113_000000 That which has not happened, could not.
5764_299665_000113_000001 The present is the necessary product of all the past, the necessary cause of all the future.
5764_299665_000114_000001 The form and motion of every star, the climate of every world, all forms of vegetable and animal life, all instinct, intelligence and conscience, all assertions and denials, all vices and virtues, all thoughts and dreams, all hopes and fears, are necessities.
5764_299665_000114_000002 Not one of the countless things and relations in the universe could have been different.
5764_299665_000118_000000 We now know that our first parents were not foreigners.
5764_299665_000118_000002 We now know, if we know anything, that the universe is natural, and that men and women have been naturally produced.
5764_299665_000118_000003 We now know our ancestors, our pedigree.
5764_299665_000118_000004 We have the family tree.
5764_299665_000119_000000 We have all the links of the chain, twenty six links inclusive from moner to man.
5764_299665_000120_000000 We did not get our information from inspired books.
5764_299665_000120_000001 We have fossil facts and living forms.
5764_299665_000122_000000 We know the paths that life has traveled.
5764_299665_000122_000001 We know the footsteps of advance.
5764_299665_000122_000002 They have been traced.
5764_299665_000122_000003 The last link has been found.
5764_299665_000124_000001 Reform.
5764_299665_000125_000000 FOR thousands of years men and women have been trying to reform the world.
5764_299665_000126_000001 I will tell them why.
5764_299665_000127_000000 Ignorance, poverty and vice are populating the world.
5764_299665_000127_000001 The gutter is a nursery.
5764_299665_000127_000003 They depend on the Lord, on luck and charity.
5764_299665_000127_000004 They are not intelligent enough to think about consequences or to feel responsibility.
5764_299665_000127_000005 At the same time they do not want children, because a child is a curse, a curse to them and to itself.
5764_299665_000127_000006 The babe is not welcome, because it is a burden.
5764_299665_000127_000007 These unwelcome children fill the jails and prisons, the asylums and hospitals, and they crowd the scaffolds.
5764_299665_000127_000009 They live by fraud and violence, and bequeath their vices to their children.
5764_299665_000129_000000 Failure seems to be the trademark of Nature.
5764_299665_000129_000001 Why?
5764_299665_000129_000002 Nature has no design, no intelligence.
5764_299665_000129_000003 Nature produces without purpose, sustains without intention and destroys without thought.
5764_299665_000129_000004 Man has a little intelligence, and he should use it.
5764_299665_000129_000005 Intelligence is the only lever capable of raising mankind.
5764_299665_000132_000000 Must the world forever remain the victim of ignorant passion?
5764_299665_000132_000001 Can the world be civilized to that degree that consequences will be taken into consideration by all?
5764_299665_000133_000000 Why should men and women have children that they cannot take care of, children that are burdens and curses?
5764_299665_000133_000001 Why?
5764_299665_000133_000002 Because they have more passion than intelligence, more passion than conscience, more passion than reason.
5764_299665_000134_000000 You cannot reform these people with tracts and talk.
5764_299665_000134_000001 You cannot reform these people with preach and creed.
5764_299665_000134_000002 Passion is, and always has been, deaf.
5764_299665_000134_000003 These weapons of reform are substantially useless.
5764_299665_000134_000004 Criminals, tramps, beggars and failures are increasing every day.
5764_299665_000134_000005 The prisons, jails, poorhouses and asylums are crowded.
5764_299665_000134_000006 Religion is helpless.
5764_299665_000134_000008 The tide of vice is rising.
5764_299665_000135_000001 Ignorance, poverty and vice must stop populating the world.
5764_299665_000135_000002 This cannot be done by moral suasion.
5764_299665_000135_000003 This cannot be done by talk or example.
5764_299665_000135_000005 This cannot be done by force, physical or moral.
5764_299665_000136_000000 To accomplish this there is but one way.
5764_299665_000136_000001 Science must make woman the owner, the mistress of herself.
5764_299665_000136_000002 Science, the only possible savior of mankind, must put it in the power of woman to decide for herself whether she will or will not become a mother.
5764_299665_000137_000000 This is the solution of the whole question.
5764_299665_000137_000002 The babes that are then born will be welcome.
5764_299665_000137_000003 They will be clasped with glad hands to happy breasts.
5764_299665_000137_000004 They will fill homes with light and joy.
5764_299665_000138_000000 Men and women who believe that slaves are purer, truer, than the free, who believe that fear is a safer guide than knowledge, that only those are really good who obey the commands of others, and that ignorance is the soil in which the perfect, perfumed flower of virtue grows, will with protesting hands hide their shocked faces.
5764_299665_000139_000000 Men and women who think that light is the enemy of virtue, that purity dwells in darkness, that it is dangerous for human beings to know themselves and the facts in Nature that affect their well being, will be horrified at the thought of making intelligence the master of passion.
5764_299665_000141_000000 When that time comes the prison walls will fall, the dungeons will be flooded with light, and the shadow of the scaffold will cease to curse the earth.
5764_299665_000141_000001 Poverty and crime will be childless.
5764_299665_000141_000002 The withered hands of want will not be stretched for alms.
5764_299665_000141_000003 They will be dust.
5764_299665_000143_000000 RELIGION can never reform mankind because religion is slavery.
6070_63485_000003_000000 CHAPTER seven.
6070_63485_000005_000002 His steps, which were somewhat irregular, in consequence of the frequent libations of the evening, were soon unheard amidst the whistling of the storm and the sheets of rain which dashed against the walls.
6070_63485_000006_000000 "They're done for," said the Schoolmaster, in a low key, to the Chouette; "out with your vitriol, and mind your eye."
6070_63485_000007_000000 "Let us take off our shoes, and then they won't hear us as we follow," suggested the Chouette.
6070_63485_000009_000000 The two monsters took off their shoes, and moved stealthily along, keeping in the shadows of the houses.
6070_63485_000009_000001 By means of this stratagem they followed so closely, that, although within a few steps of Sarah and Tom, they did not hear them.
6070_63485_000010_000001 Are you not cold, Sarah?"
6070_63485_000011_000000 "Perhaps we shall glean something from this smuggler,--this Bras Rouge," said Sarah, in a thoughtful tone, and not replying to her brother's inquiry.
6070_63485_000012_000001 We must turn back."
6070_63485_000014_000000 "I am glad they have gone that way," said the Schoolmaster, "for if the 'cove' resists, I have my own idea."
6070_63485_000015_000001 In an instant, the Schoolmaster, with a leap resembling in strength and agility the spring of a tiger, seized Seyton with one hand by the throat, and exclaimed, "Your money, or I will fling you into this hole!"
6070_63485_000016_000000 Then the brigand, pushing Seyton backwards, shoved him off his balance, and with one hand held him suspended over the mouth of the deep excavation; whilst, with his other hand, he grasped the arm of Sarah, as if in a vice.
6070_63485_000016_000001 Before Tom could make the slightest struggle, the Chouette had emptied his pockets with singular dexterity.
6070_63485_000017_000001 No," said the old brute, grumblingly, "no, not one ring.
6070_63485_000017_000002 What a shame!"
6070_63485_000018_000000 Tom Seyton did not lose his presence of mind during this scene, rapidly and unexpectedly as it had occurred.
6070_63485_000019_000000 "Will you strike a bargain?
6070_63485_000019_000001 My pocketbook contains papers quite useless to you; return it to me, and to morrow I will give you twenty five louis d'ors," said Tom to the Schoolmaster, whose hand relaxed something of its fierce gripe.
6070_63485_000020_000001 "Be off, without looking behind you, and be thankful that you have escaped so well."
6070_63485_000021_000000 "One moment," said the Chouette; "if he behaves well, he shall have his pocketbook.
6070_63485_000022_000000 "I do."
6070_63485_000024_000000 "Yes."
6070_63485_000025_000000 "Opposite saint Ouen, at the end of the road of La Revolte, the plain is wide and open.
6070_63485_000025_000001 Across the fields, one may see a long way.
6070_63485_000025_000003 Hand me the cash, and I will hand you the pocketbook."
6070_63485_000026_000000 "But he'll trap you, Chouette."
6070_63485_000027_000000 "Oh, no, he won't; I'm up to him or any of his dodges.
6070_63485_000027_000001 We can see a long way off.
6070_63485_000027_000002 I have only one eye, but that is a piercer; and if the 'cove' comes with a companion, he won't find anybody; I shall have 'mizzled.'"
6070_63485_000028_000000 A sudden idea seemed to strike Sarah, and she said to the brigand, "Will you like to gain some money?"
6070_63485_000029_000000 "Yes."
6070_63485_000031_000000 "A dandy with moustaches?
6070_63485_000031_000001 Yes, I would have stuck it into the fellow, but he did not give me time.
6070_63485_000031_000002 He stunned me with two blows of his fists, and upset me on the table,--for the first time that any man ever did so. Curses on him! but I will be revenged."
6070_63485_000034_000000 "Wretch!
6070_63485_000034_000001 I do not seek his life," replied Sarah to the Schoolmaster.
6070_63485_000035_000000 "What, then, would you have?"
6070_63485_000036_000001 I will not give you one thousand, but two thousand, francs, if you succeed."
6070_63485_000037_000001 I would go, if I were you.
6070_63485_000037_000002 Fire and smoke!
6070_63485_000037_000003 Old boy, it will pay for looking after."
6070_63485_000039_000000 "Be it so; to morrow at one."
6070_63485_000040_000000 "At one o'clock."
6070_63485_000044_000000 "Agreed."
6070_63485_000045_000000 "I will bring your pocketbook."
6070_63485_000046_000000 "And you shall have the five hundred francs I promised you, and we will agree in the other matter, if you are reasonable."
6070_63485_000047_000001 Do not follow us, or else-"
6070_63485_000049_000000 A concealed witness had been present at this transaction; it was the Chourineur, who had entered the cellars of the house to get shelter from the rain.
6070_63485_000049_000001 The proposal which Sarah made to the brigand respecting Rodolph deeply interested the Chourineur, who, alarmed for the perils which appeared about to beset his new friend, regretted that he could not warn him of them.
6070_63485_000049_000002 Perhaps his detestation of the Schoolmaster and the Chouette might have something to do with this feeling.
6070_63485_000050_000000 The Chourineur resolved to inform Rodolph of the danger which threatened him; but how?
6070_63485_000050_000001 He had forgotten the address of the self styled fan painter.
6070_63485_000051_000001 The Chourineur got up behind, and at one o'clock it stopped on the Boulevard de l'Observatoire, and Thomas and Sarah went down a narrow entrance, which was close at hand.
6070_86744_000001_000000 The first words that Albert uttered to his friend, on the following morning, contained a request that Franz would accompany him on a visit to the count; true, the young man had warmly and energetically thanked the count on the previous evening; but services such as he had rendered could never be too often acknowledged.
6070_86744_000002_000000 "My very good friend and excellent neighbor," replied the count, with a smile, "you really exaggerate my trifling exertions.
6070_86744_000003_000000 "Upon my word," said Albert, "I deserve no credit for what I could not help, namely, a determination to take everything as I found it, and to let those bandits see, that although men get into troublesome scrapes all over the world, there is no nation but the French that can smile even in the face of grim Death himself.
6070_86744_000004_000000 "Monsieur de Morcerf," replied the count, "your offer, far from surprising me, is precisely what I expected from you, and I accept it in the same spirit of hearty sincerity with which it is made;--nay, I will go still further, and say that I had previously made up my mind to ask a great favor at your hands."
6070_86744_000005_000000 "Oh, pray name it."
6070_86744_000006_000000 "I am wholly a stranger to Paris-it is a city I have never yet seen."
6070_86744_000007_000000 "Is it possible," exclaimed Albert, "that you have reached your present age without visiting the finest capital in the world?
6070_86744_000009_000000 "So distinguished an individual as yourself," cried Albert, "could scarcely have required an introduction."
6070_86744_000012_000000 "Connected by marriage, you mean," said Franz, laughingly.
6070_86744_000013_000001 Perhaps by the time you return to Paris, I shall be quite a sober, staid father of a family!
6070_86744_000013_000003 But as regards your wish to visit our fine city, my dear count, I can only say that you may command me and mine to any extent you please."
6070_86744_000015_000000 "I pledge you my honor," returned the count, "that I mean to do as I have said; both inclination and positive necessity compel me to visit Paris."
6070_86744_000016_000000 "When do you propose going thither?"
6070_86744_000017_000000 "Have you made up your mind when you shall be there yourself?"
6070_86744_000018_000000 "Certainly I have; in a fortnight or three weeks' time, that is to say, as fast as I can get there!"
6070_86744_000019_000000 "Nay," said the Count; "I will give you three months ere I join you; you see I make an ample allowance for all delays and difficulties.
6070_86744_000020_000000 "And in three months' time," said Albert, "you will be at my house?"
6070_86744_000022_000000 "Day for day, hour for hour," said Albert; "that will suit me to a dot."
6070_86744_000023_000000 "So be it, then," replied the count, and extending his hand towards a calendar, suspended near the chimney piece, he said, "to day is the twenty first of February;" and drawing out his watch, added, "it is exactly half past ten o'clock.
6070_86744_000024_000000 "Capital," exclaimed Albert; "your breakfast shall be waiting."
6070_86744_000025_000000 "Where do you live?"
6070_86744_000027_000000 "Have you bachelor's apartments there?
6070_86744_000027_000001 I hope my coming will not put you to any inconvenience."
6070_86744_000028_000000 "I reside in my father's house, but occupy a pavilion at the farther side of the court yard, entirely separated from the main building."
6070_86744_000030_000000 "Now then," said the count, returning his tablets to his pocket, "make yourself perfectly easy; the hand of your time piece will not be more accurate in marking the time than myself."
6070_86744_000031_000000 "Shall I see you again ere my departure?" asked Albert.
6070_86744_000032_000000 "That depends; when do you leave?"
6070_86744_000033_000000 "To morrow evening, at five o'clock."
6070_86744_000034_000000 "In that case I must say adieu to you, as I am compelled to go to Naples, and shall not return hither before Saturday evening or Sunday morning.
6070_86744_000035_000000 "Yes."
6070_86744_000036_000000 "For France?"
6070_86744_000037_000000 "No, for Venice; I shall remain in Italy for another year or two."
6070_86744_000038_000000 "Then we shall not meet in Paris?"
6070_86744_000039_000000 "I fear I shall not have that honor."
6070_86744_000041_000001 The young men then rose, and bowing to the count, quitted the room.
6070_86744_000041_000002 "What is the matter?" asked Albert of Franz, when they had returned to their own apartments; "you seem more than commonly thoughtful."
6070_86744_000042_000000 "I will confess to you, Albert," replied Franz, "the count is a very singular person, and the appointment you have made to meet him in Paris fills me with a thousand apprehensions."
6070_86744_000043_000001 Why, you must have lost your senses."
6070_86744_000044_000000 "Whether I am in my senses or not," answered Franz, "that is the way I feel."
6070_86744_000045_000001 Have you anything particular against him?"
6070_86744_000046_000000 "Possibly."
6070_86744_000047_000000 "Did you ever meet him previously to coming hither?"
6070_86744_000048_000000 "I have."
6070_86744_000049_000000 "And where?"
6070_86744_000051_000000 "I promise."
